---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { Fragment } from "astro/jsx-runtime";

const meta = {
  title: "About — Journal Foundation",
  description:
    "Journal Foundation stewards the open Journal Protocol Stack so developers, learners, and funders can build privacy-first ecosystems.",
  url: "https://journalfoundation.org/about",
  image: "/images/journal_network_background.png",
};
---

<BaseLayout title={meta.title} description={meta.description}>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <meta property="og:title" content={meta.title} />
    <meta property="og:description" content={meta.description} />
    <meta property="og:image" content={meta.image} />
    <meta property="og:type" content="website" />
    <meta property="og:url" content={meta.url} />
    <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image" />
    <link rel="canonical" href={meta.url} />
  </Fragment>

  <main class="about">
    <section class="hero">
      <h1>About Journal Foundation</h1>
      <p class="subhead">
        We steward open protocols for privacy-first applications—so developers can build alternatives to
        surveillance capitalism.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>What We Do</h2>
      <p>
        Journal Foundation develops and maintains open specifications for the Journal Protocol Stack—three layers
        that enable apps without platforms:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Journal Vault:</strong> Encrypted, graph-aware storage</li>
        <li><strong>Cypherlot:</strong> Capability-based sharing protocol</li>
        <li><strong>Reference implementations:</strong> Open-source SDKs and examples</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <a href="/stack">Learn about the protocol stack →</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Who We Serve</h2>

      <h3>Developers</h3>
      <p>
        We provide specifications and reference implementations so you can build privacy-first apps without
        reinventing cryptographic primitives or network protocols.
      </p>

      <h3>Privacy Advocates &amp; Learners</h3>
      <p>
        We publish educational resources about surveillance, metadata, and digital sovereignty—whether or not you
        use our protocols.
      </p>

      <h3>Researchers</h3>
      <p>
        We contribute to the academic understanding of metadata minimization, capability-based security, and
        anonymization techniques.
      </p>

      <h3>Funders</h3>
      <p>
        We practice radical transparency in governance and finance so you can support protocol development with
        confidence.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Why we exist</h2>
      <p>Humans are influenceable. That isn’t good or bad—it’s human.</p>
      <p>
        Fire warms homes when it stays in a <em>ring</em>. Knives serve us when they live in a <em>sheath</em>. The
        internet and big data are tools of the same kind: powerful, helpful, and—without guardrails—easily
        misused.
      </p>
      <p>
        When personal data sits in the open, <strong>influence pools like water under gravity</strong>—flowing toward
        those positioned to shape what we see, buy, and believe. We’re not here to fear technology. We’re here to
        <strong>use it safely</strong>: keep the fire in the ring, the knife in the sheath, and <strong>personal data in
        our custody</strong>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Respect for adjacent work</h2>
      <p>
        We applaud Solid Pods, AT Protocol/Bluesky, Mastodon, Signal/Session, and others. They solve important
        problems. Our focus is a different prerequisite: <strong>complete personal custody</strong> of arbitrarily
        large, graph-addressable data—encryption-first, capability-scoped, easy to self-host, and designed for AI
        workflows—<strong>without</strong> tokenomics or global sharding.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Founder’s note</h2>
      <p>
        I’m <strong>John Benac</strong>. I want modern intelligence—and I refuse the bargain where my data becomes
        the product. When I couldn’t find a protocol stack that kept data close, safe, and truly useful for AI, I
        followed a familiar open-source pattern. Inspired by <strong>Linux</strong>, <strong>Git</strong>, and
        <strong>Wikipedia</strong>, Journal Foundation is building <strong>Cypherlot</strong> and <strong>Journal Vault</strong> as
        simple, durable primitives—so the ecosystem that grows on top can be open, private, and human-serving.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Transparency &amp; governance</h2>
      <p>
        Funding, expenditures, roadmaps, and decisions are public.
        <a href="/governance">➡️ See governance &amp; transparency</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>FAQ</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What's the difference between Journal Foundation and the apps?</summary>
        <p>
          Journal Foundation develops <strong>protocols</strong>. Apps are built by independent developers using
          those protocols. We publish reference implementations, but anyone can build apps on the stack.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is this like Mozilla and Firefox?</summary>
        <p>
          Similar model. Mozilla Foundation stewards web standards; Firefox is one browser implementation. Journal
          Foundation stewards the protocol stack; individual apps are implementations.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Who funds this?</summary>
        <p>
          Currently bootstrapped by the founder. We're seeking funding from privacy-focused donors and grants. See
          our <a href="/governance#funding">transparency dashboard</a>.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can I use these protocols commercially?</summary>
        <p>
          Yes. The specifications are open, and the reference code is Apache 2.0 licensed. Build commercial apps,
          charge money, no restrictions.
        </p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </main>

  <style>
    .about {
      padding: 0 var(--space-md) var(--space-3xl);
    }

    .hero {
      max-width: 72ch;
      margin: var(--space-3xl) auto var(--space-xl);
    }

    .subhead {
      font-size: 1.125rem;
      color: var(--text-muted);
      margin-top: 0.75rem;
    }

    .section {
      max-width: 72ch;
      margin: var(--space-3xl) auto;
    }

    .section ul {
      padding-left: var(--space-lg);
    }

    details {
      background: var(--void-lighter);
      border: 1px solid var(--color-border-subtle);
      border-radius: 8px;
      padding: var(--space-md) var(--space-lg);
      margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
    }

    details:last-of-type {
      margin-bottom: 0;
    }

    summary {
      font-weight: 600;
      cursor: pointer;
    }

    summary::-webkit-details-marker {
      display: none;
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
